  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I was 18 he was 40. He InitIally said to me that he wIll cut his private parts if i say no to marrying him. I married him. I am unhappy what do I do?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry to hear about your situation. It sounds incredibly distressing and coercive. No one should be forced into marriage under threats. Here are some steps you can consider to address your situation:\n\n1. **Seek Immediate Safety**: If you feel threatened or unsafe, your priority should be to get to a safe place. Consider staying with family or friends, or find a local women's shelter.\n\n2. **Contact Authorities**: Given the coercive nature of your marriage, you might want to reach out to local law enforcement or a legal advisor to discuss your situation. They can provide guidance on how to handle the threat and your marriage.\n\n3. **Legal Advice**: Consult with a lawyer who specializes in family law. They can help you understand your options, including the possibility of annulment or divorce, and how to proceed safely.\n\n4. **Counseling and Support**: It's important to seek psychological support. A counselor or therapist can help you process your emotions and plan your next steps. Look for services that specialize in supporting individuals who have been through coercive or abusive relationships.\n\n5. **Financial Independence**: If you decide to leave the marriage, having some financial stability can be crucial. If possible, start setting aside money, and consider looking for employment or educational opportunities that can help support you independently.\n\n6. **Support Networks**: Reach out to trusted friends and family members. They can provide emotional support and practical help. There are also helplines and organizations focused on supporting victims of coercive control and abuse. For example, in the U.S., the National Domestic Violence Hotline can be reached at 1-800-799-SAFE (7233).\n\n7. **Plan Your Exit**: If you decide to leave, plan carefully. Ensure you have important documents (passport, ID, financial records), some money, and a safe place to go. It might be helpful to do this when you know your husband will be away from home.\n\nRemember, you deserve to live a life free from fear and coercion. It's okay to seek help and take steps towards a happier, safer future.",
